 listening, and for once, it seems prepared to learn rather than command.\",\n      \"objectives\": [\"Descend into the Diadem’s underworks with Dorn Rigger and Kelen Prism.\", \"Identify and adjust the prototype focusing array to a non-destructive standby mode.\", \"Use the Resonant Stone Tuning Fork and Shattermere inscriptions to retune the gallery away from critical frequencies.\", \"Present the Bribes Ledger copy to Nhal Vessin to compel a public audit rather than a quiet purge.\", \"Refuse Orven Caldris’s offer to liquidate oath-lanterns in exchange for silence.\", \"Seal the underworks with a joint Artificer–Tidewarden lock and record the new lens standard at the Aethral Archive.\"],\n      \"dialogue\": [\n        {\"speaker\": \"Dorn Rigger\", \"lines\": \"We learned enough to live, and sometimes that is the highest kind of knowledge a city deserves to keep. This ring could teach us to dominate, but domination is only a louder form of fear, and fear cracks glass faster than a hammer. Help me set Kelen's brilliance into a berth where it can sleep without steering the harbor, where its dreams are studied but never obeyed without consent. The hum in these hollows will follow us into old age if we get this wrong, and it will braid into our children's lullabies like a warning we forgot to heed. I brought the tuning fork cut from Ironsung's honest seam and your Shattermere copies because stone and glass remember when they are addressed politely; tonight we must speak to them with respect rather than command.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Kelen Prism\", \"lines\": \"I thought a ring could love a city the way a lens loves light, gathering it, tempering it, making it useful. I was wrong about the speed with which a heart can be fitted to a mechanism, but not about the possibility that a city's tools can be taught to care. Let me help you tune it to sleeping instead of waking, Thalen, because even dreams have rules and I have finally learned to follow them. One day we may wake it kindly and ask for partnership rather than obedience, and I will carve that day into my bones so I do not rush it again. Until then, I will be the first to bind my ambition under the oath-lanterns and accept the shame of light if I try to run ahead of the tide.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Orven Caldris\", \"lines\": \"You bring me ledgers and ask me to bless their stains, and I admire the audacity of pretending that the ink itself is not a currency already in circulation. Very well—here is my counter: sell the oath-lanterns to fund a solvent calm, and in the quiet we will move water with coin, not with throat-sung prayers to balance. You can keep your prim rituals for the alleys and the terraces; I will keep families fed when the bells ring lean, and no one will ask the light to shame a hungry child. This is the only offer that scales because it dents no keel and breaks no schedules, and because everyone pretends they do not know it is how the city has survived every crisis since the first bond was signed. Decline if you wish, but remember that public audits feed anger, and anger feeds fires, and fires melt glass into useless tears.\"},\n        {\"speaker\": \"Nhal Vessin\", \"lines\": \"No, Orven, we do not sell our shame any more than a shipwright sells the keel and claims the hull will float on promises. We will do the audit in public so the people can see where their trust has been pawned, and we will keep the lanterns where they can shame us into being better rather than richer. The city stands because its people can see their promises and hear how those promises ring under blue light, and any bargain that dims that light is a hole below the waterline. Rigger, Prism—make your peace and make me a standard that keeps a reckless hand from turning every street into a target; make me a set of notes that de-escalate by default. Thalen, finish what you started when you first heard the Diadem hum and told it you would not be bullied into genius at the co